Manpageview: Manpageview tar.i to get info file
Viewdoc: Viewdoc itemize to get latex help (if ft=tex)

tabular:
  Tabularize /regexp/
   pour aligner autour de regexp

snipmate: tab pour expander un snipset

NERDTree: explorer de fichiers
  :NERDTree

Nerdcommenter:
  \cc Comment out the current line or text selected in visual mode.
  \cn forces nesting.
  \cy Same as \cc except that the commented line(s) are yanked first.
  \c$ comment to end of lines

  \cm Comments the given lines using only one set of multipart delimiters.
  \cs Comments out the selected lines ``sexily''
  \cl, \cb  The delimiters are aligned down the left side  or both sides.

  \c<space> Toggles the comment state of the selected line(s). If the topmost selected line is commented, all selected lines are uncommented and vice versa.
  \ci Toggles the comment state of the selected line(s) individually.
  
  \cA Adds comment delimiters to the end of line and goes into insert mode between them.
  
  \ca Switches to the alternative set of delimiters.
  
  \cu Uncomments the selected line(s).

Syntastic:
  :Errors pour afficher les erreurs dans une location-list
  :SyntasticEnable filetype, :SyntasticDisable filetype

vim-space:
  'Space' en mode normal, répète la dernière action
  Shift+Space pour l'autre direction

supertab
  tab, shit-tab pour compléter

vcs:
  :Vcs*

screen: lien entre vim et un shell dans screen
  :ScreenShell command,  lancer le screen 
  :ScreenShellAttach pour se rattacher à un screen
  :ScreenSend pour envoyer le contenu au screen
  :ScreenQuit pour quitter
  bindings perso: C-s C-n new screen, C-s C-x quitter le screen, C-s C-e
      new screen avec une commande C-s C-s send to screen

